node.text:
Exciting times for Ballerina Farm!   As the family continues to grow (I’m not pregnant) so does our business.  We thought this stunning 328 acre ranch at the foot of the Uinta National Forest would be our home for a long time, but we have all of a sudden outgrown it.  It is hands down the best place I have ever lived.  Community, creek frontage, 223 days of sunshine a year, and a place where the children and animals thrive.  With tears in our eyes we are putting the ranch for sale. We have already begun the search for a new home on more land as we work to provide meat to our expanding loyal customer base. If you are a potential buyer or know someone who is, they can reach us at ranch@ballerinafarm.com for more information. 

The ranch is in prime real estate location minutes from downtown Kamas, UT, 15 min to Park City, UT and 45 min to Salt Lake City, UT.  Our ~2.7k sq ft home was historically restored to the studs in 2019 is gorgeous.  A turn key livestock ranch with impressive outbuildings and infrastructure.  $19.8k/acre. The setting is jaw dropping.  Qualified buyers only.

5 tablespoons butter (melted in your pan)
1 cup flour 
Dash of Salt 
6 eggs 
1 cup milk 

*Bake at 450 for 30 minutes or until golden brown. This recipe makes one 9x13 dish. (we always double it)!

Berry Syrup 

4 cups frozen berries 
1/2 cup sugar (a bit more if you like it sweeter) 
Lemon squeeze 
6 Tablespoons butter 

*Mix together on medium high heat until everything is incorporated and warm. 🍓 ✨

After our first baby I imagined the next children would look and act similar. Boy was I mistaken.  They are all so different in a heavenly way.  It’s amazing. Let’s talk about child #4 Frances for a minute.  She loves makeup. I on the other hand am lucky to put on a little every other day.  She is on the 6/day schedule which inspires me to get ready in the morning with more gusto.  After we took the time to get ready together today, she looked at me and said, “Mom, we should do this every day.”

Happy hens Golden Egg Serum and Warm Herbal lip tint is from @lala_earth ✨

node.text:
My preparation is underway to compete in the Mrs. America pageant in November in Las Vegas. I was crowned Mrs. Utah in May, a quick turnaround for a ranching mother of six. The best part is sharing the title with my growing family, not to mention the thrill of doing farm chores in a crown and sash. 🤠👩🏼‍🌾👸🏼All the sparkles have certainly given me more street cred with the animals.  The pigs seem particularly impressed. 

“Know your farmer, know your food” is my platform, so it seems only fitting I go from feeding pigs to practicing interview questions, milking cows to training my high heel walking, pitching hay before my pull-up routine. 💪🏻👑. Watch out, Las Vegas, here I come!

node.text: Martha is 9 months old and Daniel tells anyone in his path that it is his favorite baby age. “It’s my favorite for two reasons”, I hear him explaining to someone in shop, “they can’t walk and they can’t say ‘no’. When they start doing those two things I’m ready for the next newborn.” He has one of those voices that travels.  Across pastures, throughout the house, his voice has wings.  Most the time it’s a blessing and I enjoy hearing him from a distance, and sometimes it wakes a sleeping baby.

node.text: Hoss (our livestock guardian dog) was skeptical last month when we rolled into the barnyard and plopped a large white puppy down at his enormous paws.  He cocked his head and observed with caution. The kids named her Sally and unaware to Hoss, she was his full blooded sister from a different litter.  Exactly one year apart she reminded me of how Hoss looked just 12 months ago.  Though they quickly became pals, trouble loomed. It all started one blustery Wednesday morning when I began getting voicemails, messages, and screen shots of a local Facebook group.  Our dogs had been spotted off-farm.  Hoss had never wandered off the ranch so we were surprised and hoped it would be the last.  Before we could jump in the truck to track them down Hoss came loping into the barnyard, exhausted, but no Sally.  She was still across town. Unfortunately the wandering continued, often traveling over 3 miles away in a single night with the same outcome: Hoss retuning home alone without the puppy. When we spoke with a dog trainer about this she clarified, “they aren’t just wandering to wander, Hoss is trying to get rid of her”. With no relief in site we made the hard decision to re-home Sally to another farm.  Since she left Hoss has returned to his normal routine and hasn’t left his guard post.  Sally is thriving as the rising queen of her own farm 73 miles away.

node.text: Daniel I grew up like most kids playing sports, taking dance classes, etc.  For our kids we are leaning into rodeo events for their extracurriculars.  It is more congruent with our lifestyle, giving them an opportunity to compete with kids their age and then use those skills on the ranch to help with the family business.  We used to move all our livestock with 4 wheelers.  Then one day Daniel dismounted his wheeler to cross a ditch and on the other side got charged by an ornery steer.  Not a small cowboy, I was impressed to see how far in the air Daniel flew. He came down awkwardly on his neck and shoulder.  As I helped him off the ground he looked at me and said, “Done with the 4 wheelers, I need a horse.” What had been a slow-dawning realization for us all of a sudden came crashing down, literally. There are just places motorized vehicles physically cannot go when moving livestock.  In our realm of work, these four-legged ranch hands are as important now as they were 100 years ago.  We have loved the change and even the littles have embraced it. As our boys like to say, “We ride at dawn!”

1/4 tsp pepper 
Dash of ground cloves

1 large egg

node.text: Summers are glorious here in the mountains.  With flower-bedecked hillsides and hibernation of herb and animal ended, the ranch is alive once more.  I have moved from milking the cows inside the barn to simply milking in the pasture.  The children are rarely indoors and prefer I pack them lunches they can eat in the meadow when they head out each morning.  But then of course there are the ruthlessly long summer days.  With nearly 15 hours of daylight, we are coaxed into lengthy days of satisfyingly exhaustive work.  We go to sleep later, rise earlier, and spend a good portion of the day in the beating sun. I find myself yawning. But I have Daniel, the children, and livestock to keep me going to the next project.  P.S. dusk is magical

node.text: Recap!  My fondest childhood memories are from working in my parents flower shop.  Standing on a five gallon bucket taking orders and answering the phone.  It wasn’t easy for my parents to raise nine children selling flowers, but they did it.  Since high school, pageants have been a way to push myself and earn scholarship money for college.  The motivation for me doing another pageant was simply to keep challenging myself and a place to tell people about all the important things farmers and ranchers do for their communities.  Here are a few pictures from that special evening!  Thank you everyone for your encouragement and loud cheers near and far! 👑
